snippet.textDisplay: Trivia: you couldn't source hanwoo in the US because Korea expressly doesn't export it. Hanwoo is bred in a highly monitored way in intentionally small amounts (not much grazing land here anyway) and consumed inside the country in order to keep the quality high. Even if you took a Korean hanwoo cow to another country and made beef of it (like you can do with wagyu to get Australian wagyu for example) that beef cannot count as hanwoo because it was not raised on the terroir of Korea hanwoo country.
snippet.textOriginal: Trivia: you couldn't source hanwoo in the US because Korea expressly doesn't export it. Hanwoo is bred in a highly monitored way in intentionally small amounts (not much grazing land here anyway) and consumed inside the country in order to keep the quality high. Even if you took a Korean hanwoo cow to another country and made beef of it (like you can do with wagyu to get Australian wagyu for example) that beef cannot count as hanwoo because it was not raised on the terroir of Korea hanwoo country.

That ain't Ram-don at all.... You have to boil instant noodle only with water, not adding seasoning until it is completely done.
After boiling noodle, you have to throw away water but leave some water as much as 7~8 spoonful.
Add seasoning of both noodles, each goes to half. Then mix it well then that's original Ram-don.
